        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Infrared observations indicate a minimum gas mass (assuming gas-to-dust ratio of 100) of 0.5 to 1 Solar mass.   Extrapolating to 350 GHz, at D = 7 kpc, an envelope containing  1 Solar mass of  gas is expected to produce a total flux = 1.4 – 4 mJy for a dust temperature of 20 K.  Mid-IR observations show that the inner edge of the 5” radius ring has a dust temperature of  85 K.  If most of the gas is in a compact ring, or if the dispersed dust is this warm, the expect continuum flux from dust is  9 – 24 mJy.  

To resolve the ring, an angular resolution of 1" is required.  At this resolution, ALMA has about 30 beams along the ring.   For 85 K dust concentrated the expected flux per beam is about 0.3 mJy.  Thus, a continuum sensitivity of 0.07 mJy in a 1” beam is required.

The corresponding spectral line sensitivity is about 30 mK.  At this sensitivity, CO will be detected with high signal-to noise for normal ISM abundance of 7e-5.  A 30 mK requirement enables a sensitive search.  

Spectral Setup:  In the Phase 1, we specify 4 1.8 GHz bands to be observed with ~1.5 km/s spectral resolution.  These bands include the brightest 0.85 mm lines expected from an RSG envelope.   In Phase II, we will included additional, higher resolution sub-bands to target specific tracers which in single-dish data have narrow line-widths. 

Lines to be observed include:  12CO J=3-2, HCN J=4-3, HCO+ J=4-3, and CS J=7-6.  

A full bandwidth of ~8 GHz is needed to cover as many available molecular tracers as possible and to maximize continuum sensitivity.   Thus, a high data rate is needed to achieve the continuum sensitivity and 1" resolution.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
